# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: building-energy-management
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] BAS functionality may keep a building's climate within a specified range, provide light to rooms based on occupancy, monitor performance and device failures, and provide malfunction alarms to building maintenance staff.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] A BAS works to reduce building energy and maintenance costs compared to a non-controlled building.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Most commercial, institutional, and industrial buildings built after 2000 include a BAS, whilst older buildings may be retrofitted with a new BAS.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] A building controlled by a BAS is often referred to as an "intelligent building", a "smart building", or (if a residence) a *smart home*.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Commercial and industrial buildings have historically relied on robust proven protocols (like BACnet) while proprietary protocols (like X-10) were used in homes.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] With the advent of wireless sensor networks and the Internet of Things, an increasing number of smart buildings are resorting to using low-power wireless communication technologies such as Zigbee, Bluetooth Low Energy and LoRa to interconnect the local sensors, actuators and processing devices.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Almost all multi-story green buildings are designed to accommodate a BAS for the energy, air and water conservation characteristics.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Electrical device demand response is a typical function of a BAS, as is the more sophisticated ventilation and humidity monitoring required of "tight" insulated buildings.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Most green buildings also use as many low-power DC devices as possible.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Even a passivhaus design intended to consume no net energy whatsoever will typically require a BAS to manage heat capture, shading and venting, and scheduling device use.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Building management systems are most commonly implemented in large projects with extensive mechanical, HVAC, and electrical systems.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Systems linked to a BMS typically represent 40% of a building's energy usage; if lighting is included, this number approaches to 70%.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] BMS systems are a critical component to managing energy demand.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Improperly configured BMS systems are believed to account for 20% of building energy usage, or approximately 8% of total energy usage in the United States.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] In addition to controlling the building's internal environment, BMS systems are sometimes linked to access control (turnstiles and access doors controlling who is allowed access and egress to the building) or other security systems such as closed-circuit television (CCTV) and motion detectors.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Fire alarm systems and elevators are also sometimes linked to a BMS for monitoring.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] In case a fire is detected then only the fire alarm panel could close dampers in the ventilation system to stop smoke spreading, shut down air handlers, start smoke evacuation fans, and send all the elevators to the ground floor and park them to prevent people from using them.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Building management systems have also included disaster-response mechanisms (such as base isolation) to save structures from earthquakes.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] In more recent times, companies and governments have been working to find similar solutions for flood zones and coastal areas at-risk to rising sea levels.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Self-adjusting floating environment draws from existing technologies used to float concrete bridges and runways such as Washington's SR 520 and Japan's Mega-Float.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Analog inputs are used to read a variable measurement.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Examples are temperature, humidity and pressure sensors which could be thermistor, 4–20 mA, 0–10 volt or platinum resistance thermometer (resistance temperature detector), or wireless sensors.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] A digital input indicates a device is on or off.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Some examples of digital inputs would be a door contact switch, a current switch, an air flow switch, or a voltage-free relay contact (dry contact).
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Digital inputs could also be pulse inputs counting the pulses over a period of time.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] An example is a turbine flow meter transmitting flow data as a frequency of pulses to an input.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Nonintrusive load monitoring is software relying on digital sensors and algorithms to discover appliance or other loads from electrical or magnetic characteristics of the circuit.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] It is however detecting the event by an analog means.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] These are extremely cost-effective in operation and useful not only for identification but to detect start-up transients, line or equipment faults, etc.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Occupancy sensors detect the presence, number, and sometimes location of people in a space to enable demand-controlled systems for lighting, HVAC, and energy management.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Traditional examples include passive infrared (PIR), ultrasonic, and CO2-based detectors, but advanced systems use low-resolution thermal imaging or area sensors to provide zone-level accuracy without capturing identifiable images, ensuring privacy compliance (e.g., GDPR).
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] These sensors output analog heat signatures or digital counts that integrate with building management systems via protocols like BACnet or wireless IoT networks, reducing energy use by up to 40% through precise ventilation and lighting control.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Analog outputs control the speed or position of a device, such as a variable frequency drive, an I-P (current to pneumatics) transducer, or a valve or damper actuator.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] An example is a hot water valve opening up 25% to maintain a setpoint.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Another example is a variable frequency drive ramping up a motor slowly to avoid a hard start.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Digital outputs are used to open and close relays and switches as well as drive a load upon command.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] An example would be to turn on the parking lot lights when a photocell indicates it is dark outside.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Another example would be to open a valve by allowing 24VDC/AC to pass through the output powering the valve.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Analog outputs could also be pulse type outputs emitting a frequency of pulses over a given period of time.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] An example is an energy meter calculating kWh and emitting a frequency of pulses accordingly.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Controllers are essentially small, purpose-built computers with input and output capabilities.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] These controllers come in a range of sizes and capabilities to control devices commonly found in buildings, and to control sub-networks of controllers.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Inputs allow a controller to read temperature, humidity, pressure, current flow, air flow, and other essential factors.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] The outputs allow the controller to send command and control signals to slave devices, and to other parts of the system.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Inputs and outputs can be either digital or analog.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Digital outputs are also sometimes called discrete depending on manufacturer.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Controllers used for building automation can be grouped in three categories: programmable logic controllers (PLCs), system/network controllers, and terminal unit controllers.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] However an additional device can also exist in order to integrate third-party systems (e.g. a stand-alone AC system) into a central building automation system.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Terminal unit controllers usually are suited for control of lighting and/or simpler devices such as a package rooftop unit, heat pump, VAV box, fan coil, etc.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] The installer typically selects one of the available pre-programmed personalities best suited to the device to be controlled, and does not have to create new control logic.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Occupancy is one of two or more operating modes for a building automation system; unoccupied, morning warmup, and night-time setback are other common modes.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Occupancy is usually based on time of day schedules.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] In occupancy mode, the BAS aims to provides a comfortable climate and adequate lighting, often with zone-based control so that users on one side of a building have a different thermostat (or a different system, or sub system) than users on the opposite side.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] A temperature sensor in the zone provides feedback to the controller, so it can deliver heating or cooling as needed.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] If enabled, morning warmup (MWU) mode occurs prior to occupancy.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] During morning warmup the BAS tries to bring the building to setpoint just in time for occupancy.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] The BAS often factors in outdoor conditions and historical experience to optimize MWU.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] This is also referred to as *optimized start*.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Some buildings rely on occupancy sensors to activate lighting or climate conditioning.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Given the potential for long lead times before a space becomes sufficiently cool or warm, climate conditioning is not often initiated directly by an occupancy sensor.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Lighting can be turned on, off, or dimmed with a building automation or lighting control system based on time of day, or on occupancy sensor, photosensors and timers.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] One typical example is to turn the lights in a space on for a half-hour since the last motion was sensed.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] A photocell placed outside a building can sense darkness, and the time of day, and modulate lights in outer offices and the parking lot.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Lighting is also a good candidate for demand response, with many control systems providing the ability to dim (or turn off) lights to take advantage of DR incentives and savings.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] In newer buildings, the lighting control can be based on the field bus Digital Addressable Lighting Interface (DALI).
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Lamps with DALI ballasts are fully dimmable.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] DALI can also detect lamp and ballast failures on DALI luminaires and signals failures.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Shading and glazing are essential components in the building system, they affect occupants' visual, acoustical, and thermal comfort and provide the occupant with a view outdoor.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Automated shading and glazing systems are solutions for controlling solar heat gains and glare.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] It refers to the use of technology to control external or internal shading devices (such as blinds, and shades) or glazing itself.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] The system has an active and rapid response to various changing outdoor data (such as solar, wind) and to changing interior environment (such as temperature, illuminance, and occupant demands).
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Building shading and glazing systems can contribute to thermal and lighting improvement from both energy conservation and comfort point of view.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Dynamic shading devices allow the control of daylight and solar energy to enter into built environment in relation to outdoor conditions, daylighting demands and solar positions.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] The common products include venetian blinds, roller shades, louvers, and shutters.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] They are mostly installed on the interior side of the glazing system because of the low maintenance cost, but also can be used on the exterior or a combination of both.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Most air handlers mix return and outside air so less temperature/humidity conditioning is needed.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] This can save money by using less chilled or heated water (not all AHUs use chilled or hot water circuits).
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Some external air is needed to keep the building's air healthy.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] To optimize energy efficiency while maintaining healthy indoor air quality (IAQ), demand control (or controlled) ventilation (DCV) adjusts the amount of outside air based on measured levels of occupancy.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Analog or digital temperature sensors may be placed in the space or room, the return and supply air ducts, and sometimes the external air.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Actuators are placed on the hot and chilled water valves, the outside air and return air dampers.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] The supply fan (and return if applicable) is started and stopped based on either time of day, temperatures, building pressures or a combination.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] All modern building automation systems have alarm capabilities.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] It does little good to detect a potentially hazardous or costly situation if no one who can solve the problem is notified.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Notification can be through a computer (email or text message), pager, cellular phone voice call, audible alarm, or all of these.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] For insurance and liability purposes all systems keep logs of who was notified, when and how.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Alarms may immediately notify someone or only notify when alarms build to some threshold of seriousness or urgency.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] At sites with several buildings, momentary power failures can cause hundreds or thousands of alarms from equipment that has shut down – these should be suppressed and recognized as symptoms of a larger failure.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Some sites are programmed so that critical alarms are automatically re-sent at varying intervals.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] For example, a repeating critical alarm (of an uninterruptible power supply in 'bypass') might resound at 10 minutes, 30 minutes, and every 2 to 4 hours thereafter until the alarms are resolved.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Security systems can be interlocked to a building automation system.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] If occupancy sensors are present, they can also be used as burglar alarms.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Because security systems are often deliberately sabotaged, at least some detectors or cameras should have battery backup and wireless connectivity and the ability to trigger alarms when disconnected.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Modern systems typically use power-over-Ethernet (which can operate a pan-tilt-zoom camera and other devices up to 30–90 watts) which is capable of charging such batteries and keeps wireless networks free for genuinely wireless applications, such as backup communication in outage.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Fire alarm panels and their related smoke alarm systems are usually hard-wired to override building automation.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] For example: if the smoke alarm is activated, all the outside air dampers close to prevent air coming into the building, and an exhaust system can isolate the blaze.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Similarly, electrical fault detection systems can turn entire circuits off, regardless of the number of alarms this triggers or persons this distresses.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Fossil fuel combustion devices also tend to have their own over-rides, such as natural gas feed lines that turn off when slow pressure drops are detected (indicating a leak), or when excess methane is detected in the building's air supply.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] ASHRAE's open protocol BACnet or the open protocol LonTalk specify how most such devices interoperate.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Modern systems use SNMP to track events, building on decades of history with SNMP-based protocols in the computer networking world.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Physical connectivity between devices was historically provided by dedicated optical fiber, ethernet, ARCNET, RS-232, RS-485 or a low-bandwidth special purpose wireless network.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Modern systems rely on standards-based multi-protocol heterogeneous networking such as that specified in the IEEE 1905.1 standard and verified by the nVoy auditing mark.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Proprietary hardware dominates the controller market.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Each company has controllers for specific applications.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Some are designed with limited controls and no interoperability, such as simple packaged roof top units for HVAC.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Software will typically not integrate well with packages from other vendors.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Cooperation is at the Zigbee/BACnet/LonTalk level only.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Current systems provide interoperability at the application level, allowing users to mix-and-match devices from different manufacturers, and to provide integration with other compatible building control systems.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] These typically rely on SNMP, long used for this same purpose to integrate diverse computer networking devices into one coherent network.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] With the growing spectrum of capabilities and connections to the Internet of Things, building automation systems were repeatedly reported to be vulnerable, allowing hackers and cybercriminals to attack their components.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Buildings can be exploited by hackers to measure or change their environment: sensors allow surveillance (e.g. monitoring movements of employees or habits of inhabitants) while actuators allow to perform actions in buildings (e.g. opening doors or windows for intruders).
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] Several vendors and committees started to improve the security features in their products and standards, including KNX, Zigbee and BACnet (see recent standards or standard drafts).
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] However, researchers report several open problems in building automation security.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] On November 11, 2019, a 132-page security research paper was released titled "I Own Your Building (Management System)" by Gjoko Krstic and Sipke Mellema that addressed more than 100 vulnerabilities affecting various BMS and access control solutions by various vendors.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] On November 24, 2025, a 161-page security research paper was released titled "Project Brainfog: Beyond the Facade - Exposing Smart Giants" by Gjoko Krstic that addressed more than 1000 vulnerabilities affecting two widely used BAS controllers by ABB Group.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] It is common for room automation systems to employ a touchscreen as the primary way of controlling each operation.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] On November 27, 2018, a 29-page research paper titled "A Scalable Room Occupancy Prediction with Transferable Time Series Decomposition of CO2 Sensor Data" was published by Irvan Bastian Arief, Margaret Hamilton, and Flora Salim.
[src:building-energy-management/building-automation] The paper introduced a novel approach to leveraging carbon dioxide (CO2) sensor data to predict room occupancy—enabling smarter building automation by estimating the number of occupants in a room at any given time.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] From a physical point of view, a building is a very complex system, influenced by a wide range of parameters.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] A simulation model is an abstraction of the real building which allows to consider the influences on high level of detail and to analyze key performance indicators without cost-intensive measurements.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] BPS is a technology of considerable potential that provides the ability to quantify and compare the relative cost and performance attributes of a proposed design in a realistic manner and at relatively low effort and cost.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Energy demand, indoor environmental quality (incl. thermal and visual comfort, indoor air quality and moisture phenomena), HVAC and renewable system performance, urban level modeling, building automation, and operational optimization are important aspects of BPS.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Over the last six decades, numerous BPS computer programs have been developed.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] The most comprehensive listing of BPS software can be found in the BEST directory.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Some of them only cover certain parts of BPS (e.g. climate analysis, thermal comfort, energy calculations, plant modeling, daylight simulation etc.).
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] The core tools in the field of BPS are multi-domain, dynamic, whole-building simulation tools, which provide users with key indicators such as heating and cooling load, energy demand, temperature trends, humidity, thermal and visual comfort indicators, air pollutants, ecological impact and costs.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] The ease of input and accessibility of output data varies widely between BPS tools.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Advanced whole-building simulation tools are able to consider almost all of the following in some way with different approaches.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] The history of BPS is approximately as long as that of computers.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] The very early developments in this direction started in the late 1950s and early 1960s in the United States and Sweden.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] During this period, several methods had been introduced for analyzing single system components (e.g. gas boiler) using steady state calculations.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] The very first reported simulation tool for buildings was **BRIS**, introduced in 1963 by the Royal Institute of Technology in Stockholm.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Until the late 1960s, several models with hourly resolution had been developed focusing on energy assessments and heating/cooling load calculations.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] This effort resulted in more powerful simulation engines released in the early 1970s, among which were BLAST, DOE-2, ESP-r, HVACSIM+ and TRNSYS.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] In the United States, the 1970s energy crisis intensified these efforts, as reducing the energy consumption of buildings became an urgent domestic policy interest.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] The energy crisis also initiated development of U.S. building energy standards, beginning with ASHRAE 90-75.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] The development of building simulation represents a combined effort between academia, governmental institutions, industry, and professional organizations.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Over the past decades the building simulation discipline has matured into a field that offers unique expertise, methods and tools for building performance evaluation.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Several review papers and state of the art analysis were carried out during that time giving an overview about the development.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] In the 1980s, a discussion about future directions for BPS among a group of leading building simulation specialists started.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] There was a consensus that most of the tools, that had been developed until then, were too rigid in their structure to be able to accommodate the improvements and flexibility that would be called for in the future.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Around this time, the very first equation-based building simulation environment **ENET** was developed, which provided the foundation of **SPARK**.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] In 1989, Sahlin and Sowell presented a **Neutral Model Format** (NMF) for building simulation models, which is used today in the commercial software IDA ICE.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Four years later, Klein introduced the **Engineering Equation Solver** (EES) and in 1997, Mattsson and Elmqvist reported on an international effort to design **Modelica**.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] BPS still presents challenges relating to problem representation, support for performance appraisal, enabling operational application, and delivering user education, training, and accreditation.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Clarke (2015) describes a future vision of BPS with the following, most important tasks which should be addressed by the global BPS community.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] In the context of building simulation models, **error** refers to the discrepancy between simulation results and the actual measured performance of the building.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] There are normally occurring uncertainties in building design and building assessment, which generally stem from approximations in model inputs, such as occupancy behavior.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] **Calibration** refers to the process of "tuning" or adjusting assumed simulation model inputs to match observed data from the utilities or Building Management System (BMS).
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] The number of publications dealing with accuracy in building modeling and simulation increased significantly over the past decade.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Many papers report large gaps between simulation results and measurements, while other studies show that they can match very well.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] The reliability of results from BPS depends on many different things, e.g. on the quality of input data, the competence of the simulation engineers and on the applied methods in the simulation engine.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] An overview about possible causes for the widely discussed performance gap from design stage to operation is given by de Wilde (2014) and a progress report by the Zero Carbon Hub (2013).
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Both conclude the factors mentioned above as the main uncertainties in BPS.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] ASHRAE Standard 140-2017 "Standard Method of Test for the Evaluation of Building Energy Analysis Computer Programs (ANSI Approved)" provides a method to validate the technical capability and range of applicability of computer programs to calculate thermal performance.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] ASHRAE Guideline 4-2014 provides performance indices criteria for model calibration.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] The performance indices used are normalized mean bias error (NMBE), coefficient of variation (CV) of the root mean square error (RMSE), and R2 (coefficient of determination).
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] ASHRAE recommends a R2 greater than 0.75 for calibrated models.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] The criteria for NMBE and CV RMSE depends on if measured data is available at a monthly or hourly timescale.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Given the complexity of building energy and mass flows, it is generally not possible to find an analytical solution, so the simulation software employs other techniques, such as response function methods, or numerical methods in finite differences or finite volume, as an approximation.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Most of today's whole building simulation programs formulate models using imperative programming languages.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] These languages assign values to variables, declare the sequence of execution of these assignments and change the state of the program, as is done for example in C/C++, Fortran or MATLAB/Simulink.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] In such programs, model equations are tightly connected to the solution methods, often by making the solution procedure part of the actual model equations.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] The use of imperative programming languages limits the applicability and extensibility of models.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] More flexibility offer simulation engines using symbolic Differential Algebraic Equations (DAEs) with general purpose solvers that increase model reuse, transparency and accuracy.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Since some of these engines have been developed for more than 20 years (e.g.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] IDA ICE) and due to the key advantages of equation-based modeling, these simulation engines can be considered as state of the art technology.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Building simulation models may be developed for both new or existing buildings.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] There are hundreds of software tools available for simulating the performance of buildings and building subsystems, which range in capability from whole-building simulations to model input calibration to building auditing.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Among whole-building simulation software tools, it is important to draw a distinction between the ***simulation engine***, which dynamically solves equations rooted in thermodynamics and building science, and the ***modeler application (interface)***.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Most modeler applications support the user with a graphical user interface to make data input easier.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] The modeler creates an input file for the simulation engine to solve.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] The engine returns output data to the modeler application or another visualization tool which in turn presents the results to the user.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] For some software packages, the calculation engine and the interface may be the same product.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] The table below gives an overview about commonly used simulation engines and modeler applications for BPS.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Since the 1990s, building performance simulation has undergone the transition from a method used mainly for research to a design tool for mainstream industrial projects.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] However, the use in different countries still varies greatly.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Building certification programs like LEED (USA), BREEAM (UK) or DGNB (Germany) have shown to be a good driving force for BPS to find broader application.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Also, national building standards that allow BPS based analysis are of good help for an increasing industrial adoption, such as in the United States (ASHRAE 90.1), Sweden (BBR), Switzerland (SIA) and the United Kingdom (NCM).
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] The Swedish building regulations are unique in that computed energy use has to be verified by measurements within the first two years of building operation.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Since the introduction in 2007, experience shows that highly detailed simulation models are preferred by modelers to reliably achieve the required level of accuracy.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Furthermore, this has fostered a simulation culture where the design predictions are close to the actual performance.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] This in turn has led to offers of formal energy guarantees based on simulated predictions, highlighting the general business potential of BPS.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] In a performance-based approach, compliance with building codes or standards is based on the predicted energy use from a building simulation, rather than a prescriptive approach, which requires adherence to stipulated technologies or design features.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] Performance-based compliance provides greater flexibility in the building design as it allows designers to miss some prescriptive requirements if the impact on building performance can be offset by exceeding other prescriptive requirements.
[src:building-energy-management/building-energy-simulation] The certifying agency provides details on model inputs, software specifications, and performance requirements.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] An **energy audit** is an inspection survey and an analysis of energy flows for energy conservation in a building.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] It may include a process or system to reduce the amount of energy input into the system without negatively affecting the output.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] In commercial and industrial real estate, an energy audit is the first step in identifying opportunities to reduce energy expense and carbon footprint.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] When the object of study is an occupied building then reducing energy consumption while maintaining or improving human comfort, health and safety are of primary concern.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Beyond simply identifying the sources of energy use, an energy audit seeks to prioritize the energy uses according to the greatest to least cost-effective opportunities for energy savings.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] A *home energy audit* is a service where the energy efficiency of a house is evaluated by a person using professional equipment (such as blower doors and infrared cameras), with the aim to suggest the best ways to improve energy efficiency in heating and cooling the house.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] An energy audit of a home may involve recording various characteristics of the building envelope including the walls, ceilings, floors, doors, windows, and skylights.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] For each of these components the area and resistance to heat flow (R-value) is measured or estimated.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] The leakage rate or infiltration of air through the building envelope is of concern, which can be affected by window construction and quality of door seals such as weatherstripping.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] This exercise aims to quantify the building's overall thermal performance.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] The audit may also assess the efficiency, physical condition, and programming of mechanical systems such as the heating, ventilation, air conditioning equipment, and thermostat.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] A home energy audit may include a written report estimating energy use given local climate criteria, thermostat settings, roof overhang, and solar orientation.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] This could show energy use for a given time period, say a year, and the impact of any suggested improvements per year.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] The accuracy of energy estimates are greatly improved when the homeowner's billing history is available showing the quantities of electricity, natural gas, fuel oil, or other energy sources consumed over a one or two-year period.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Some of the greatest effects on energy use are user behavior, climate, and age of the home.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] An energy audit may therefore include an interview of the homeowners to understand their patterns of use over time.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] The energy billing history from the local utility company can be calibrated using heating degree day and cooling degree day data obtained from recent, local weather data in combination with the thermal energy model of the building.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Advances in computer-based thermal modeling can take into account many variables affecting energy use.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] A home energy audit is often used to identify cost effective ways to improve the comfort and efficiency of buildings.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] In addition, homes may qualify for energy efficiency grants from central government.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Recently, the improvement of smartphone technology has enabled homeowners to perform relatively sophisticated energy audits of their own homes.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] This technique has been identified as a method to accelerate energy efficiency improvements.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Utility companies may provide this service, and loans and other incentives.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Some public utilities offer energy audits as part of a coordinated service to plan or install home energy upgrades.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Utilities may also provide incentives to switch, for example, if you are an oil customer considering switching to natural gas.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Residential energy auditors are accredited by the Building Performance Institute (BPI) or the Residential Energy Services Network (RESNET).
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] There are also some simplified tools available, with which a homeowner can quickly assess energy improvement potential.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Often these are supplied for free by state agencies or local utilities, who produce a report with estimates of usage by device/area (since they have usage information already).
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Examples include the Energy Trust of Oregon program and the Seattle Home Resource Profile.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Such programs may also include free compact fluorescent lights.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] A simple do-it-yourself home energy audit can be performed without using any specialized tools.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] With an attentive and planned assessment, a homeowner can spot many problems that cause energy losses and make decisions about possible energy efficiency upgrades.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] During a home energy audit it is important to have a checklist of areas that were inspected and problems identified.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Once the audit is completed, a plan for suggested actions needs to be developed.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] In New York City, local laws such as Local Law 87 require buildings larger than 50,000 square feet (4,600 m2) to have an energy audit once every ten years, as assigned by its parcel number.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Energy auditors must be certified to perform this work, although there is no oversight to enforce the rule.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Because Local Law 87 requires a licensed Professional Engineer to oversee the work, choosing a well-established engineering firm is the safest route.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] These laws are the results of New York City's PlaNYC to reduce energy used by buildings, which is the greatest source of pollution in New York City.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Some engineering firms provide free energy audits for facilities committed to implementing the energy saving measures found.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Since 2002, The Lebanese Center for Energy Conservation (LCEC) initiated a nationwide program on energy audits for medium and large consuming facilities.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] By the end of 2008, LCEC has financed and supervised more than 100 audits.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] LCEC launched an energy audit program to assist Lebanese energy consuming tertiary and public buildings and industrial plants in the management of their energy through this program.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] The long-term objective of LCEC is to create a market for ESCOs, whereby any beneficiary can contact directly a specialized ESCO to conduct an energy audit, implement energy conservation measures and monitor energy saving program according to a standardized energy performance contract.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Currently, LCEC is helping in the funding of the energy audit study and thus is linking both the beneficiary and the energy audit firm.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] LCEC also targets the creation of a special fund used for the implementation of the energy conservation measures resulting from the study.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] LCEC set a minimum standard for the ESCOs qualifications in Lebanon and published a list of qualified ESCOs on its website.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Increasingly in the last several decades, industrial energy audits have exploded as the demand to lower increasingly expensive energy costs and move towards a sustainable future have made energy audits greatly important.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Their importance is magnified since energy spending is a major expense to industrial companies (energy spending accounts for ~ 10% of the average manufacturer's expenses).
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] This growing trend should only continue as energy costs continue to rise.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] While the overall concept is similar to a home or residential energy audit, industrial energy audits require a different skillset.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Weatherproofing and insulating a house are the main focus of residential energy audits.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] For industrial applications, it is the HVAC, lighting, and production equipment that use the most energy, and hence are the primary focus of energy audits.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Numerous audit procedures have been developed for non-residential (tertiary) buildings (ASHRAE; IEA-EBC Annex 11; Krarti, 2000).
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Audit is required to identify the most efficient and cost-effective Energy Conservation Opportunities (ECOs) or Measures (ECMs).
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Energy conservation opportunities (or measures) can consist in more efficient use or of partial or global replacement of the existing installation.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Common types/levels of energy audits are distinguished below, although the actual tasks performed and level of effort may vary with the consultant providing services under these broad headings.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] The only way to ensure that a proposed audit will meet your specific needs is to spell out those requirements in a detailed scope of work.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Taking the time to prepare a formal solicitation will also assure the building owner of receiving competitive and comparable proposals.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] The impossibility of describing all possible situations that might be encountered during an audit means that it is necessary to find a way of describing what constitutes good, average and bad energy performance across a range of situations.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] The aim of benchmarking is to answer this question.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Benchmarking mainly consists in comparing the measured consumption with reference consumption of other similar buildings or generated by simulation tools to identify excessive or unacceptable running costs.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] As mentioned before, benchmarking is also necessary to identify buildings presenting interesting energy saving potential.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] An important issue in benchmarking is the use of performance indices to characterize the building.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Typically, benchmarks are established based on the energy outlets (loads) within the building and are then further parsed into "base loads" and "weather sensitive loads".
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] These are established through a simple regression analysis of energy consumption and demand (if metered) correlated to weather (temperature and degree - day) data during the period for which utility data is available.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Aggregate base loads will represent as the intercept of this regression and the slope will typically represent the combination of building envelope conduction and infiltration losses less losses or gains from the base loads themselves.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] For example, while lighting is typically a base load, the heat generated from that lighting must be subtracted from the weather sensitive cooling load derived from the slope to gain an accurate picture of the true contribution of the building envelope on cooling energy use and demand.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] The preliminary audit (alternatively called a simple audit, screening audit or walk-through audit) is the simplest and quickest type of audit.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] It involves minimal interviews with site-operating personnel, a brief review of facility utility bills and other operating data, and a walk-through of the facility to become familiar with the building operation and to identify any glaring areas of energy waste or inefficiency.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Typically, only major problem areas will be covered during this type of audit.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Corrective measures are briefly described, and quick estimates of implementation cost, potential operating cost savings, and simple payback periods are provided.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] A list of energy conservation measures (ECMs, or energy conservation opportunities, ECOs) requiring further consideration is also provided.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] This level of detail, while not sufficient for reaching a final decision on implementing proposed measure, is adequate to prioritize energy-efficiency projects and to determine the need for a more detailed audit.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Utility bills are collected for a 12- to 36-month period to allow the auditor to evaluate the facility's energy demand rate structures and energy usage profiles.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] If interval meter data is available, the detailed energy profiles that such data makes possible will typically be analyzed for signs of energy waste.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Additional metering of specific energy-consuming systems is often performed to supplement utility data.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] In-depth interviews with facility operating personnel are conducted to provide a better understanding of major energy consuming systems and to gain insight into short- and longer-term energy consumption patterns.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] This type of audit will be able to identify all energy-conservation measures appropriate for the facility, given its operating parameters.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] A detailed financial analysis is performed for each measure based on detailed implementation cost estimates, site-specific operating cost savings, and the customer's investment criteria.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Sufficient detail is provided to justify project implementation.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] The evolution of cloud-based energy auditing software platforms is enabling the managers of commercial buildings to collaborate with general and specialty trades contractors in performing general and energy system-specific audits.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] The benefit of software-enabled collaboration is the ability to identify the full range of energy efficiency options that may be applicable to the specific building under study with "live time" cost and benefit estimates supplied by local contractors.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] In most corporate settings, upgrades to a facility's energy infrastructure must compete for capital funding with non-energy-related investments.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Both energy and non-energy investments are rated on a single set of financial criteria that generally stress the expected return on investment (ROI).
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] The projected operating savings from the implementation of energy projects must be developed such that they provide a high level of confidence.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] In fact, investors often demand guaranteed savings.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] The investment-grade audit expands on the detailed audit described above and relies on a complete engineering study in order to detail technical and economical issues necessary to justify the investment related to the transformations.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] A complete audit procedure, very similar to the ones proposed by ASHRAE and Krarti (2000), has been proposed in the frame of the AUDITAC and HARMONAC projects to help in the implementation of the EPB (“Energy Performance of Buildings”) directive in Europe and to fit to the current European market.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] The advent of high-resolution thermography has enabled inspectors to identify potential issues within the building envelope by taking a thermal image of the various surfaces of a building.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] For purposes of an energy audit, the thermographer will analyze the patterns within the surface temperatures to identify heat transfer through convection, radiation, or conduction.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] The thermography *only* identifies *surface* temperatures, and analysis must be applied to determine the reasons for the patterns within the surface temperatures.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Thermal analysis of a home generally costs between 300 and 600 dollars.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] For those who cannot afford a thermal inspection, it is possible to get a general feel for the heat loss with a non-contact infrared thermometer and several sheets of reflective insulation.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] The method involves measuring the temperatures on the inside surfaces of several exterior walls to establish baseline temperatures.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] The best manner in which to do this is when the temperature differential (Delta T) between the inside and outside of the structure is at least 40 degrees.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] A well-insulated wall will commonly change approximately 1 degree per hour if the difference between external and internal temperatures is an average of 40 degrees.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] A poorly insulated wall can drop as much as 10 degrees in an hour.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] With increases in carbon dioxide emissions or other greenhouse gases, pollution audits are now a prominent factor in most energy audits.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Implementing energy efficient technologies help prevent utility generated pollution.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Online pollution and emission calculators can help approximate the emissions of other prominent air pollutants in addition to carbon dioxide.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Pollution audits generally take electricity and heating fuel consumption numbers over a two-year period and provide approximations for carbon dioxide, VOCs, nitrous oxides, carbon monoxide, sulfur dioxide, mercury, cadmium, lead, mercury compounds, cadmium compounds and lead compounds.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Energy audits initially became popular in response to the energy crisis of 1973 and later years.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Interest in energy audits has recently increased as a result of growing understanding of human impact upon global warming and climate change.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-audit] Energy audits are also popular due to financial incentives for homeowners.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] The concept of sustainability, or ecological design, ensures that the use of current resources does not adversely affect future society's well-being or render it impossible to obtain resources for other uses in the long term.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] The term "sustainability" in relation to architecture has so far been mostly considered through the lens of building technology and its transformations.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Going beyond the technical sphere of "green design", invention and expertise, some scholars are starting to position architecture within a much broader cultural framework of the human interrelationship with nature.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Adopting this framework allows for tracing a rich history of cultural debates about humanity's relationship to nature and the environment, from the point of view of different historical and geographical contexts.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Critics of the reductionism of modernism often noted the abandonment of the teaching of architectural history as a causal factor.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] The fact that a number of the major players in the deviation from modernism were trained at Princeton University's School of Architecture, where recourse to history continued to be a part of design training in the 1940s and 1950s, was significant.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] The increasing rise of interest in history had a profound impact on architectural education.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] History courses became more typical and regularized.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] With the demand for professors knowledgeable in the history of architecture, several PhD programs in schools of architecture arose in order to differentiate themselves from art history PhD programs, where architectural historians had previously trained.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] In the US, MIT and Cornell were the first, created in the mid-1970s, followed by Columbia, Berkeley, and Princeton.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Global construction accounts for 38% of total global emissions.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] While sustainable architecture and construction standards have traditionally focused on reducing operational carbon emissions, there are to date few standards or systems in place to track and reduce embodied carbon.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] While steel and other materials are responsible for large-scale emissions, cement alone is responsible for 8% of all emissions.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Energy efficiency over the entire life cycle of a building is a primary goal of sustainable architecture.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Architects use many different passive and active techniques to reduce the energy needs of buildings and increase their ability to capture or generate their own energy.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] To minimize cost and complexity, sustainable architecture prioritizes passive systems to take advantage of building location with incorporated architectural elements, supplementing with renewable energy sources and then fossil fuel resources only as needed.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Site analysis can be employed to optimize use of local environmental resources such as daylight and ambient wind for heating and ventilation.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Energy use very often depends on whether the building is on-grid or off-grid.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Off-grid buildings do not use energy provided by utility services and instead have their own independent energy production.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] They use on-site electricity storage while on-grid sites feed in excessive electricity back to the grid.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Numerous passive architectural strategies have been developed over time.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Examples of such strategies include the arrangement of rooms or the sizing and orientation of windows in a building, and the orientation of facades and streets or the ratio between building heights and street widths for urban planning.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] An important and cost-effective element of an efficient heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC) system is a well-insulated building.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] A more efficient building requires less heat generating or dissipating power, but may require more ventilation capacity to expel polluted indoor air.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Significant amounts of energy are flushed out of buildings in the water, air and compost streams.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Off the shelf, on-site energy recycling technologies can effectively recapture energy from waste hot water and stale air and transfer that energy into incoming fresh cold water or fresh air.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Recapture of energy for uses other than gardening from compost leaving buildings requires centralized anaerobic digesters.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Copper, versus other metal conductors, helps to improve the electrical energy efficiencies of motors, thereby enhancing the sustainability of electrical building components.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Site and building orientation have some major effects on a building's HVAC efficiency.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Passive solar building design allows buildings to harness the energy of the sun efficiently without the use of any active solar mechanisms such as photovoltaic cells or solar hot water panels.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Typically, passive solar building designs incorporate materials with high thermal mass that retain heat effectively and strong insulation that works to prevent heat escape.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Low energy designs also require the use of solar shading, by means of awnings, blinds or shutters, to reduce the solar heat gain in summer and to reduce the need for artificial cooling.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] In addition, low energy buildings typically have a very low surface area to volume ratio to minimize heat loss.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] This means that sprawling multi-winged building designs (sometimes thought to look more "organic") are generally avoided in favor of more centralized structures.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Traditional cold climate buildings such as American colonial saltbox designs provide a good historical model for centralized heat efficiency in a small-scale building.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Windows are placed to maximize the input of heat-creating light while minimizing the loss of heat through glass, a poor insulator.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] In the northern hemisphere this usually involves installing a large number of south-facing windows to collect direct sun and severely restricting the number of north-facing windows.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Certain window types, such as double or triple glazed insulated windows with gas filled spaces and low emissivity (low-E) coatings, provide much better insulation than single-pane glass windows.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Preventing excess solar gain by means of solar shading devices in the summer months is important to reduce cooling needs.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Deciduous trees are often planted in front of windows to block excessive sun in summer with their leaves but allow light through in winter when their leaves fall off.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Louvers or light shelves are installed to allow the sunlight in during the winter (when the sun is lower in the sky) and keep it out in the summer (when the sun is high in the sky).
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] They are slatted like shutters and reflect light and radiation to reduce glare on the interior space.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Advanced louver systems are automated to maximize daylight and monitor the interior temperature by adjusting their tilt.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Coniferous or evergreen plants are often planted to the north of buildings to shield against cold north winds.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] In colder climates, heating systems are a primary focus for sustainable architecture because they are typically one of the largest single energy drains in buildings.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] In warmer climates where cooling is a primary concern, passive solar designs can also be very effective.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Masonry building materials with high thermal mass are very valuable for retaining the cool temperatures of night throughout the day.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] In addition builders often opt for sprawling single story structures in order to maximize surface area and heat loss.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Buildings are often designed to capture and channel existing winds, particularly the especially cool winds coming from nearby bodies of water.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Many of these valuable strategies are employed in some way by the traditional architecture of warm regions, such as south-western mission buildings.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Active solar devices such as photovoltaic solar panels help to provide sustainable electricity for any use.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Electrical output of a solar panel is dependent on orientation, efficiency, latitude, and climate—solar gain varies even at the same latitude.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Typical efficiencies for commercially available PV panels range from 4% to 28%.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] The low efficiency of certain photovoltaic panels can significantly affect the payback period of their installation.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] This low efficiency does not mean that solar panels are not a viable energy alternative.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] In Germany, for example, solar panels are commonly installed in residential home construction.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Roofs are often angled toward the sun to allow photovoltaic panels to collect at maximum efficiency.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] In the northern hemisphere, a true-south facing orientation maximizes yield for solar panels.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] If true-south is not possible, solar panels can produce adequate energy if aligned within 30° of south.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] However, at higher latitudes, winter energy yield will be significantly reduced for non-south orientation.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] To maximize efficiency in winter, the collector can be angled above horizontal Latitude +15°.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] To maximize efficiency in summer, the angle should be Latitude -15°.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] However, for an annual maximum production, the angle of the panel above horizontal should be equal to its latitude.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] The use of undersized wind turbines in energy production in sustainable structures requires the consideration of many factors.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] In considering costs, small wind systems are generally more expensive than larger wind turbines relative to the amount of energy they produce.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] For small wind turbines, maintenance costs can be a deciding factor at sites with marginal wind-harnessing capabilities.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] At low-wind sites, maintenance can consume much of a small wind turbine's revenue.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Wind turbines begin operating when winds reach 8 mph, achieve energy production capacity at speeds of 32-37 mph, and shut off to avoid damage at speeds exceeding 55 mph.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] The energy potential of a wind turbine is proportional to the square of the length of its blades and to the cube of the speed at which its blades spin.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Though wind turbines are available that can supplement power for a single building, because of these factors, the efficiency of the wind turbine depends much upon the wind conditions at the building site.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] For these reasons, for wind turbines to be at all efficient, they must be installed at locations that are known to receive a constant amount of wind (with average wind speeds of more than 15 mph), rather than locations that receive wind sporadically.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] A small wind turbine can be installed on a roof.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Installation issues then include the strength of the roof, vibration, and the turbulence caused by the roof ledge.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Small-scale rooftop wind turbines have been known to be able to generate power from 10% to up to 25% of the electricity required of a regular domestic household dwelling.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Turbines for residential scale use are usually between 7 feet (2 m) to 25 feet (8 m) in diameter and produce electricity at a rate of 900 watts to 10,000 watts at their tested wind speed.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] The reliability of wind turbine systems is important to the success of a wind energy project.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Unanticipated breakdowns can have a significant impact on a project's profitability due to the logistical and practical difficulties of replacing critical components in a wind turbine.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Uncertainty with the long-term component reliability has a direct impact on the amount of confidence associated with cost of energy (COE) estimates.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Solar water heaters, also called solar domestic hot water systems, can be a cost-effective way to generate hot water for a home.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] They can be used in any climate, and the fuel they use—sunshine—is free.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] There are two types of solar water systems: active and passive.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] An active solar collector system can produce about 80 to 100 gallons of hot water per day.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] A passive system will have a lower capacity.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Active solar water system's efficiency is 35-80% while a passive system is 30-50%, making active solar systems more powerful.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] There are also two types of circulation, direct circulation systems and indirect circulation systems.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Direct circulation systems loop the domestic water through the panels.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] They should not be used in climates with temperatures below freezing.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Indirect circulation loops glycol or some other fluid through the solar panels and uses a heat exchanger to heat up the domestic water.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] The two most common types of collector panels are flat-plate and evacuated-tube.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] The two work similarly except that evacuated tubes do not convectively lose heat, which greatly improves their efficiency (5%–25% more efficient).
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] With these higher efficiencies, Evacuated-tube solar collectors can also produce higher-temperature space heating, and even higher temperatures for absorption cooling systems.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Electric-resistance water heaters that are common in homes today have an electrical demand around 4500 kW·h/year.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] With the use of solar collectors, the energy use is cut in half.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] The up-front cost of installing solar collectors is high, but with the annual energy savings, payback periods are relatively short.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Air source heat pumps (ASHP) can be thought of as reversible air conditioners.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Like an air conditioner, an ASHP can take heat from a relatively cool space (e.g. a house at 70 °F) and dump it into a hot place (e.g. outside at 85 °F).
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] However, unlike an air conditioner, the condenser and evaporator of an ASHP can switch roles and absorb heat from the cool outside air and dump it into a warm house.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Air-source heat pumps are inexpensive relative to other heat pump systems.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] As the efficiency of air-source heat pumps decline when the outdoor temperature is very cold or very hot; therefore, they are most efficiently used in temperate climates.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] However, contrary to earlier expectations, they have proven to be also well suited for regions with cold outdoor temperatures, such as Scandinavia or Alaska.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] In Norway, Finland and Sweden, the use of heat pumps has grown strongly over the last two decades: in 2019, there were 15–25 heat pumps per 100 inhabitants in these countries, with ASHP the dominant heat pump technology.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Similarly, earlier assumptions that ASHP would only work well in fully insulated buildings have proven wrong—even old, partially insulated buildings can be retrofitted with ASHPs and thereby strongly reduce their energy demand.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Effects of EAHPs (exhaust air heat pumps) have also been studied within the aforementioned regions displaying promising results.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] An exhaust air heat pump uses electricity to extract heat from exhaust air leaving a building, redirecting it towards DHW (domestic hot water), space heating, and warming supply air.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] In colder countries, an EAHP may be able to recover around 2 - 3 times more energy than an air-to-air exchange system.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] A 2022 study surrounding projected emission decreases within Sweden's Kymenlaakso region explored the aspect of retrofitting existing apartment buildings (of varying ages) with EAHP systems.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Select buildings were chosen in the cities of Kotka and Kouvola, their projected carbon emissions decreasing by about 590 tCO2 and 944 tCO2 respectively with a 7 - 13 year payoff period.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] It is, however, important to note that EAHP systems may not produce favourable results if installed in a building exhibiting incompatible exhaust output rates or electricity consumption.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] In this case, EAHP systems may increase energy bills without providing reasonable cuts to carbon emissions (see EAHP).
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Ground-source (or geothermal) heat pumps provide an efficient alternative.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] The difference between the two heat pumps is that the ground-source has one of its heat exchangers placed underground—usually in a horizontal or vertical arrangement.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Ground-source takes advantage of the relatively constant, mild temperatures underground, which means their efficiencies can be much greater than that of an air-source heat pump.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] The in-ground heat exchanger generally needs a considerable amount of area.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Designers have placed them in an open area next to the building or underneath a parking lot.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Energy Star ground-source heat pumps can be 40% to 60% more efficient than their air-source counterparts.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] They are also quieter and can also be applied to other functions like domestic hot water heating.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] In terms of initial cost, the ground-source heat pump system costs about twice as much as a standard air-source heat pump to be installed.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] However, the up-front costs can be more than offset by the decrease in energy costs.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] The reduction in energy costs is especially apparent in areas with typically hot summers and cold winters.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Other types of heat pumps are water-source and air-earth.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] If the building is located near a body of water, the pond or lake could be used as a heat source or sink.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Air-earth heat pumps circulate the building's air through underground ducts.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] With higher fan power requirements and inefficient heat transfer, Air-earth heat pumps are generally not practical for major construction.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Passive daytime radiative cooling harvests the extreme coldness of outer space as a renewable energy source to achieve daytime cooling.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] These cooling surfaces can be applied as sky-facing panels, similar to other renewable energy sources like solar energy panels, making them for simple integration into architectural design.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] A passive daytime radiative cooling roof application can double the energy savings of a white roof, and when applied as a multilayer surface to 10% of a building's roof, it can replace 35% of air conditioning used during the hottest hours of daytime.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Bamboo flooring can be useful in ecological spaces since they help reduce pollution particles in the air.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Vegetative cover or shield over building envelopes also helps in the same.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Paper which is fabricated or manufactured out of forest wood is supposedly one hundred percent recyclable, thus it regenerates and saves almost all the forest wood that it takes during its manufacturing process.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] There is an underutilized potential for systematically storing carbon in the built environment.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] The use of natural building materials for their sustainable qualities is a practice seen in vernacular architecture.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Regional architectural styles develop over generations, utilizing local materials.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] This practice reduces transportation and production emissions.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Regenerative sources, use of waste material, and the ability to reuse are sustainable qualities of timber, thatching, and stone and clay.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Laminated timber products, straw, and stone are low carbon construction materials with major potential for scalability.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Timber products can sequester carbon, while stone has a low extraction energy.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Straw, including straw-bale construction, sequesters carbon while providing a high level of insulation.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] High thermal performance of natural materials contribute to regulating interior conditions without the use of modern technologies.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] The uses of timber, straw, and stone in sustainable architecture were the subject of a major exhibit at the UK's Design Museum.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Sustainable architecture often incorporates the use of recycled or second hand materials, such as reclaimed lumber and recycled copper.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] The reduction in use of new materials creates a corresponding reduction in embodied energy (energy used in the production of materials).
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Often sustainable architects attempt to retrofit old structures to serve new needs in order to avoid unnecessary development.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Architectural salvage and reclaimed materials are used when appropriate.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] When older buildings are demolished, frequently any good wood is reclaimed, renewed, and sold as flooring.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Any good dimension stone is similarly reclaimed.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Many other parts are reused as well, such as doors, windows, mantels, and hardware, thus reducing the consumption of new goods.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] When possible, building materials may be gleaned from the site itself; for example, if a new structure is being constructed in a wooded area, wood from the trees which were cut to make room for the building would be re-used as part of the building itself.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] To discourage insect damage, these alternate insulation materials may be treated with boric acid.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Organic or milk-based paints may be used.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] However, a common fallacy is that "green" materials are always better for the health of occupants or the environment.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Many harmful substances (including formaldehyde, arsenic, and asbestos) are naturally occurring and are not without their histories of use with the best of intentions.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] A study of emissions from materials by the State of California has shown that there are some green materials that have substantial emissions whereas some more "traditional" materials actually were lower emitters.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Thus, the subject of emissions must be carefully investigated before concluding that natural materials are always the healthiest alternatives for occupants and for the Earth.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Volatile organic compounds (VOC) can be found in any indoor environment coming from a variety of different sources.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] VOCs have a high vapor pressure and low water solubility, and are suspected of causing sick building syndrome type symptoms.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Green products are usually considered to contain fewer VOCs and be better for human and environmental health.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Commonly used building materials such as wood require deforestation that is, without proper care, unsustainable.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] As of October 2022, researchers at MIT have made developments on lab-grown *Zinnia elegans* cells growing into specific characteristics under conditions within their control.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] These characteristics include the "shape, thickness, [and] stiffness," as well as mechanical properties that can mimic wood.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Bengston from the USDA suggests that this alternative would be more efficient than traditional wood harvesting, with future developments potentially saving on transportation energy and conserve forests.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] However, Bengston notes that this breakthrough would change paradigms and raises new economic and environmental questions, such as timber-dependent communities′ jobs or how conservation would impact wildfires.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Despite the importance of materials to overall building sustainability, quantifying and evaluating the sustainability of building materials has proven difficult.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] There is little coherence in the measurement and assessment of materials sustainability attributes, resulting in a landscape today that is littered with hundreds of competing, inconsistent and often imprecise eco-labels, standards and certifications.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] This discord has led both to confusion among consumers and commercial purchasers and to the incorporation of inconsistent sustainability criteria in larger building certification programs such as LEED.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Various proposals have been made regarding rationalization of the standardization landscape for sustainable building materials.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Building information modelling (BIM) is used to help enable sustainable design by allowing architects and engineers to integrate and analyze building performance.[5].
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] BIM services, including conceptual and topographic modelling, offer a new channel to green building with successive and immediate availability of internally coherent, and trustworthy project information.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] BIM enables designers to quantify the environmental impacts of systems and materials to support the decisions needed to design sustainable buildings.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] A sustainable building consultant may be engaged early in the design process, to forecast the sustainability implications of building materials, orientation, glazing and other physical factors, so as to identify a sustainable approach that meets the specific requirements of a project.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Norms and standards have been formalized by performance-based rating systems e.g.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] They define benchmarks to be met and provide metrics and testing to meet those benchmarks.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] It is up to the parties involved in the project to determine the best approach to meet those standards.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] One central and often ignored aspect of sustainable architecture is building placement.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Although the ideal environmental home or office structure is often envisioned as an isolated place, this kind of placement is usually detrimental to the environment.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] First, such structures often serve as the unknowing frontlines of suburban sprawl.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Second, they usually increase the energy consumption required for transportation and lead to unnecessary auto emissions.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Ideally, most building should avoid suburban sprawl in favor of the kind of light urban development articulated by the New Urbanist movement.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Careful mixed use zoning can make commercial, residential, and light industrial areas more accessible for those traveling by foot, bicycle, or public transit, as proposed in the Principles of Intelligent Urbanism.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] The study of permaculture, in its holistic application, can also greatly help in proper building placement that minimizes energy consumption and works with the surroundings rather than against them, especially in rural and forested zones.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Sustainable buildings look for ways to conserve water.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] One strategic water saving design green buildings incorporate are green roofs.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Green roofs have rooftop vegetation which captures storm drainage water.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] This function not only collects the water for further uses but also serves as a good insulator that can aid in the urban heat island effect.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Another strategic water efficient design is treating wastewater so it can be reused again.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Another sustainable design strategy is the use of rainwater harvesting systems, such as low-flow fixtures.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] These are widely known in green architecture for reducing water consumption exponentially and supporting long-term resource conservation.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Sustainable urbanism takes actions beyond sustainable architecture, and makes a broader view for sustainability.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Typical solutions include eco-industrial park (EIP) and urban agriculture.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] International programs that are being supported include Sustainable Urban Development Network, supported by UN-HABITAT; and Eco2 Cities, supported by the World Bank.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Concurrently, the recent movements of New Urbanism, New Classical architecture and contemporary Traditional architecture promote a sustainable approach towards construction, that appreciates and develops smart growth, architectural tradition and classical design.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] This in contrast to modernist and globally uniform architecture, as well as leaning against solitary housing estates and suburban sprawl.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] The Driehaus Architecture Prize is an award that recognizes efforts in New Urbanism and New Classical architecture, and is endowed with a prize money twice as high as that of the modernist Pritzker Prize.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Waste takes the form of spent or useless materials generated from households and businesses, construction and demolition processes, and manufacturing and agricultural industries.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] These materials are loosely categorized as municipal solid waste, construction and demolition (C&D) debris, and industrial or agricultural by-products.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] Sustainable architecture focuses on the on-site use of waste management, incorporating things such as grey water systems for use on garden beds, and composting toilets to reduce sewage.
[src:building-energy-management/energy-efficiency-in-buildings] These methods, when combined with on-site food waste composting and off-site recycling, can reduce a house's waste to a small amount of packaging waste.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] An **occupancy sensor** is an indoor device used to detect the presence of a person.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Applications include automatic adjustment of lights or temperature or ventilation systems in response to the quantity of people present.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] The sensors typically use infrared, ultrasonic, microwave, or other technology.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] The term encompasses devices as different as PIR sensors, hotel room keycard locks and smart meters.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Occupancy sensors are typically used to save energy, provide automatic control, and comply with building codes.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] A vacancy sensor works like an occupancy sensor, however, lights must be manually turned ON, but will automatically turn OFF when motion is no longer detected.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Environmental sensors, such as temperature, humidity and CO2 sensors, which detect the change in the environment due to the presence of a human.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Ultrasonic sensors, similar to radar. they work on the doppler shift principle.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] An ultrasonic sensor will send high frequency sound waves in area and will check for their reflected patterns.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] If the reflected pattern is changing continuously then it assumes that there is occupancy and the lighting load connected is turned on.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] If the reflected pattern is the same for a preset time then the sensor assumes there is no occupancy and the load is switched off.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Similar to the ultrasonic sensor, a microwave sensor also works on the doppler shift principle.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] A microwave sensor will send high frequency microwaves in an area and will check for their reflected patterns.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] A microwave sensor has high sensitivity as well as detection range compared to other types of sensors.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Keycard light slots, used in a hotel energy management system to detect when a hotel room is occupied, by requiring the guest to place their keycard in a slot to activate lights and thermostats.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Smart meters, which work by detecting the change in power consumption patterns that exhibit distinct characteristics for occupied and vacant states.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Barometric Pressure sensors can be used to monitor door openings, which are associated with foot traffic, in rooms containing positive pressure, including operating rooms.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Human sensing (via people counting) became widespread in 2020 as companies installed AI cameras and occupancy sensors to enforce social distancing and capacity limits during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE), detect occupancy by linking to nearby devices with a dedicated app, but they miss people without the app or misread presence if a device is left behind.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Motion sensors are often used in indoor spaces to control electric lighting.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] If no motion is detected, it is assumed that the space is empty, and thus does not need to be lit.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Turning off the lights in such circumstances can save substantial amounts of energy.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] In lighting practice occupancy sensors are sometimes also called "presence sensors" or "vacancy sensors".
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] LSG's Pixelview, Philips Lumimotion, Ecoamicatechs Sirius etc.) also classify the number of occupants, their direction of motion, etc., through image processing.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Pixelview is a camera-based occupancy sensor, using a camera that is built into each light fixture.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Occupancy sensors for lighting control typically use infrared (IR), ultrasonic, tomographic motion detection, microwave sensors, or camera-based sensors (image processing).
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] The field of view of the sensor must be carefully selected/adjusted so that it responds only to motion in the space served by the controlled lighting.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] For example, an occupancy sensor controlling lights in an office should not detect motion in the corridor outside the office.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Tomographic motion detection systems have the unique benefit of detecting motion through walls and obstructions, yet do not trigger as easily from motion on the outside of the detection area like traditional microwave sensors.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Sensors and their placement are never perfect, therefore most systems incorporate a delay time before switching.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] This delay time is often user-selectable, but a typical default value is 15 minutes.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] This means that the sensor must detect no motion for the entire delay time before the lights are switched.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Most systems switch lights off at the end of the delay time, but more sophisticated systems with dimming technology reduce lighting slowly to a minimum level (or zero) over several minutes, to minimize the potential disruption in adjacent spaces.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] If lights are off and an occupant re-enters a space, most current systems switch lights back on when motion is detected.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] However, systems designed to switch lights off automatically with no occupancy, and that require the occupant to switch lights on when they re-enter are gaining in popularity due to their potential for increased energy savings.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] These savings accrue because in a spaces with access to daylight the occupant may decide on their return that they no longer require supplemental electric light.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] The prototype utilized existing ultrasonic intrusion alarm technology coupled to conventional industrial timers, with basic switching elements.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] First prototype was crafted on a plywood base; the first model required a separate transmitter and receiver processing 20,200 cycles per second of sound energy.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Fraser was employed by and developed the device for the Embarcadero Center high-rise office complex in San Francisco, and as such employee did not profit from the invention.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] He took the concept to Unisec security devices and had them build a single piece transceiver based on 277VAC - the level of electricity used for commercial lighting in the Embarcadero Center complex.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Four hundred of these units were installed under a newly named UNENCO brand, and installed in the bathrooms of the four high-rise towers.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] This application received Congressional Mention for Kevin Fraser's efforts, as well as various Pacific Gas & Electric awards.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Noted local columnist Herb Cain made mention that one should not sit too long in the stalls at Embarcadero Center, and the word caught on regarding the technology.
[src:building-energy-management/occupancy-sensor] Fraser was acknowledged by the Association of Energy Engineers (AEE) as the inventor.
